text: My name is Yoshikage Kira. I'm 33 years old. My house is in the northeast section of Morioh, where all the villas are, and I am not married. I work as an employee for the Kame Yu department stores, and I get home every day by 8 PM at the latest. I don't smoke, but I occasionally drink. I'm in bed by 11 PM, and make sure I get eight hours of sleep, no matter what. After having a glass of warm milk and doing about twenty minutes of stretches before going to bed, I usually have no problems sleeping until morning. Just like a baby, I wake up without any fatigue or stress in the morning. I was told there were no issues at my last check-up. I'm trying to explain that I'm a person who wishes to live a very quiet life. I take care not to trouble myself with any enemies, like winning and losing, that would cause me to lose sleep at night. That is how I deal with society, and I know that is what brings me happiness. Although, if I were to fight I wouldn't lose to anyone.

text: Freddie was playing around with Bohemian Rhapsody for about as long as somebody normally produces an entire album. He kept on adding and changing to the point of obsession, and the studio and others didn't even like it. It was a waste of time and money. And it was really freaking weird. But then a buddy "accidentally" slipped a bit of it onto radio and apologized for the yet released mixup. But people were hooked. These mistakes made their way to America with bits and pieces of the song being heard. Finally Bohemian Rhapsody was released with overwhelming success. All while few believed in Freddie's strange genius. At least that's how I heard the story. I'm no historian. Take that with a grain of salt.

text: Well, I think the trailer looks really great from the view of a Freddie Mercury and Queen fan. But if they were going to focus on that they should have left any romantic/sexual references out of the trailer and as a member of the LGBT community I have to agree with Bryan Fuller's complaints, it looks like they hetwashed the trailer to attract or not to scare away mainstream audiences.  How that will be in the full movie remains to be seen. But that wouldn't be the first time, even a major success like Black Panther did it, albeit with fictional, comic book characters. Some of the big Hollywood studios are still too much dominated by the same old ignorant fools, despite all the lip service and token bones they throw us and think they're enough to shut us up. And yeah, this "life-threatening illness" is called AIDS, one of the most talked about, politically instrumentalized and feared illnesses of the last decades, which has, not exclusively, but first and foremost plagued homosexually active men. There is no need to be coy about it and not naming that in your description is almost an insult to its victims including the main protagonist of this movie, at the least it's f*cking direspectful. The legacy and inspiration you talk about in the end is as much a result of Freddie's uncompromising character and life as the music. Sure, he was sometimes rather elusive about that, but that doesn't give you the right to tailor it around the fact that it might make you and parts of your potential audience uncomfortable. Okay, maybe money does give you the right in this world, but at least not without being called out for.  My excitement for this project has definitely taken a hit today...

text: Freddie was a great performer but he led many to their deaths. Worshipped by masses, he outperformed himself and died ignominiously destroying the truth of life by his glory of choral sexual ecstacy, drugs, promiscuity, homosexuality and the inordinate love of the body. All those things God the creator spoke against. And in the end he died a broken man in a terrible state which was the antithesis of what he promoted and dreamed of in a sexual utopia. The Bohemian rhapsody was prophetic. It wasabout himself, because such belief in oneself ultimately ends in abysmal failure and catastrophe and the departure from reality. His life was dramatic, not to be despised but most certainly not to be emanated or glorified.

text: Rami has really captured the physical side of Freddie.In two minds about film ....is it just going to be the caricature of Mercury all camp quips or will it get under the skin of this huge icon who still endears and fascinates millions so many years later.I have read its up to Live Aid which again is a double edged sword and did leave me thinking if this is a big hit will there be a sequel as morbid and flippant as that sounds.I really don't know if its noble or a cop out to eradicate the second half of Freddie's story ,I think its a given they'll show Freddies early 80s increasing consumptions hinting at what was to come.I cannot tell if this will be big box office at all I just hope its not the anodyne soft focus biopics that the James Brown,Jimi Hendrix ones have been.But it has to be said Queen have really remained in the publics heart and imaginations.I don't think a day goes by where I don't hear at least 4 Queen songs on the radio their music has lived on and embarrassed a lot of their harsh critics at the time.And Freddie was a very very special performer who we won't see the likes of again.

text: Finally we get a peek at this film. I’m super stoked and can’t wait to see it. As all movies go they sometimes have inaccuracies and i just spotted one i think. I may be wrong and i welcome all my fellow Queen fans to correct me if i am but at 0:14 there’s a shot of Freddie decked in Zandra Rhodes with Brian behind him wearing the same and playing an Ovation pacemaker 1615  12 string guitar. Now as far as i know he didn’t start playing the ovation until 1977. The Zandra Rhodes winged costume was worn between 73-75. Although Brian did wear it once at the Earls Court concert in 1977 but Freddie stopped using his winged costume in 1975. I still can’t wait to see the film tho and i really hope they not only use the hits but also the hidden gems which were part of their live act in the early 70s like “White Queen”, “Son And Daughter” and of course “In The Lap Of The Gods (revisited)”.

text: I have a theory as to why Freddie Mercury lived and died the way he did. Picture a young Indian kid born in complete isolation and obscurity in Zanzibar. From an early age he is regimented deeply in the Parsi religion and spends his formative years in prep schools in Mumbai. The idea of becoming a famous rock musician was absolutely never in the cards for him or his family. The Zanzibar uprising happens and the family flees to England and the rest is history. Had the uprising not happened who knows what would how history would have played out for this ostentatious young man.     When he rose to become a powerful and wealthy musician everything from that point must have seemed like magic because it was so unexpected. Freddie therefore responds by indulging and completely immersing himself in the Rock and Roll lifestyle. He commits to every creative inclination, every moment and every vice with complete abandon.     When you achieve a dream that seemed way beyond your realm of recognition and appears too good to be true there is a sense that you might lose it all at any time. This is what drove Freddie to be as creative, larger than life and ultimately self destructive as he was, the irony is that in the end he did lose everything even as he created an enduring legacy in music.
author: Maverick Artitude Entertainment

text: For those who want to know what songs are used in this trailer:  Trailer starts with a copy of *Freddie's call and audience response from the 1985 Live Aid performance* (the "day-oh"s). Then we hear a mash-up of *Another One Bites the Dust* (base riff), *Bohemian Rhapsody* ("ooh baby," "just gotta get out"), and *Killer Queen* . Then a guitar riff from *Bohemian Rhapsody* before the first bit of dialog.  Then it's a mash-up of "the operatic section" from *Bohemian Rhapsody* and *We Will Rock You* ... "Six bloody minutes?!" And finishing with *We Will Rock You* .  Hope this helps!

text: For anyone who thinks that the movie is "hetero-washed," this is for you. In the trailer the only girl Freddie shows interest in is Mary Austin, the girl for which Love of My Life was written. Yes they dated for a while, but then they realized it wouldn't work out and they broke up, but remained friends for the rest of his life. He left nearly all of his possessions (including his house and his beloved cats) to Mary instead of with his partner because he loved and trusted her so much. Obviously, she should be a big part of this movie. This was also the 1970s and 80s. You couldn't just come out like you can now. It was dangerous. Freddie hid his homosexuality from nearly everyone in the 70s. He didn't even understand it until the late 70s, in fact, he and Kenny Everett (the guy who played BoRhap constantly on his radio program) sort of figured it out together.   It's going to be great. I'm glad they didn't ignore Mary because she's an important part of the story one hardly ever gets to hear.
author: Maille Gray

text: I watched the movie today and I'm very disappointed. Shallow story, they didn't get into Freddy's mind/psyche at all, didn't REALLY show how and why he became such a blue bird and artist, everything in this movie is flat and fast. They didn't show how the band really got together or how they worked on their music in details, it was rather just a few quick musical montages and that is it. Solid entertainment in the second half of the movie, great Live Aid part, yes, but not much more. Sorry, but real Queen fan, who wanted raw, real, complex, deep, uncompromising truth and story - just cannot like this movie. Mercury and all the Queen deserves much better, their story has so much potential (wasted in this movie), which is weird to say and how it all turned out, considering living Queen members were involved in this movie. Sorry guys, you did awful job. I guess I'll just wait for another movie, bold and great this time, I hope. And no, Malek doesn't deserve Oscar for this one. He is doing his best, but ultimately it's just shallow script and except very good mannerism, and maybe one, really emotional scene with Mary (in the rain) there is no depth in this role/Malek's work.
